														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-821579">
									

<p>Actually, no. We're not.</p>
<p>Of the +20,000 combinations, most of them would have <em>no effect whatsoever</em>.</p>
<p>For instance, there's no need to see what happens to someone when all the dysprosium in his body (0 atoms / kg) is transformed into lanthanum.</p>
<p>The SCP Foundation is not <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Unit_731">Unit 731</a>. We do not employ Josef Mengele.</p>
<p>Yes, sometimes our tests kill our test subjects in horribly grotesque ways. But that's not the reason for the tests.</p>
<p>And part of the point of chemistry is a <em>systematization</em> of knowledge. The hydrogen=&gt;helium test was useful, and now we know exactly what will happen for hydrogen=&gt;neon, hydrogen=&gt;argon, hydrogen=&gt;krypton, etc.</p>

							</div>

								
					
